      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Walter Snow was an American radical writer and poet.  Snow contributed to many radical periodicals including <emph render="italic">American Dialog</emph>, <emph render="italic">Left Review</emph>, <emph render="italic">The Rebel Poet</emph>, and <emph render="italic">New Masses</emph>, and wrote a collection pf poetry entitled <emph render="italic">Glory and the Shame</emph>.  He served as editor of <emph render="italic">The Anvil</emph>, "the proletarian fiction magazine," from April 1935 to October 1935.  </p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Walter Snow Collection</emph> consists of a copy of the radical periodical <emph render="italic">The Anvil</emph> marked up with Snow's notes to compositor, and a letter from Snow to Liberal Press with detailed layout notes.  The letter is dated April 2, 1935, and thus likely represents the first changes Snow wanted to make as incoming editor.  Also included in a copy of American Book Collector with mention of Snow (p. 16) and Snow's comments in the margins.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
